HaskHell

Target IP: 10.10.9.224
Challenge Description: Show your professor that his PhD isn't in security.

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan shows there are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH on port 22, and maybe a HTTP on port 5001, as shown above.


I performed an aggressive port scan against the two open ports and obtained the result above.


The target machine seems to be using the technology above. One interesting information is the gunicorn/19.7.1. I will start enumeration with the HTTP application on port 5001.

Enumeration

Port 5001: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this web application. There is a hyperlink homework here that can be clicked, as shown above.


Pressing the homework here button displays the webpage above. There is another hyperlink here that can be pressed. However, pressing this button returns the error 404 Not Found. Apparently there is a way to submit Haskell homework files to the target machine. The submitted files are compiled, executed, and the output is redirected to a file under the uploads directory. Time to find where I can upload Haskell files.


Performing a directory search against this web application using the command feroxbuster -u http://10.10.9.224:5001/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x php,html,txt -d 3 with feroxbuster returns an interesting directory called /submit, as shown above.


And bingo! I found the location to upload Haskell files at /submit, as shown above. Maybe I can upload my reverse shell here?


I created a simple Haskell reverse shell script shown above. I saved the code above in a file called shell.hs. Time to upload this to obtain a reverse shell connection from the target machine.

Exploitation


I started a listener on port 8443 on my machine. And then I uploaded the malicious Haskell reverse shell file. After a few seconds, I obtained a reverse shell connection from the target machine on my machine at port 8443. Now I have a foothold on the target machine with the session as flask, as shown above.

Privilege Escalation


I can access the SSH key of the user prof, as shown above. I copied this key to my machine. It is not encrypted either, so I do not need to enter the passphrase.


I changed the permission of the key to 400. And then using the command ssh -i id_rsa prof@10.10.9.224, I connected to the target machine with the SSH key of user prof successfully. Now I have a foothold as the user prof. I also successfully elevated my privileges horizontally from the user flask to user prof, as shown above.


Running sudo -l shows the command /usr/bin/flask run can be executed as the user root.


The content of the flask is shown above. I do not have the privileges to modify this script. I tried module hijacking, but I had no luck either.


Executing the flask binary with the command run outputs the message above.


And running flask --help shows the useful information above. Maybe I can create my own flask app and get it to execute as the user root.


I created a Python file called pe.py. This contains the code import pty;pty.spawn("/bin/bash"); to open a bash shell. Since this gets executed by the root user, it will open a root bash shell. And using the command sudo /usr/bin/flask run, I obtained a root bash shell. Now I have root access on the target machine :)
